      Azeri-Russian rift
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/ruptly-editor-detained-sputnik-raid-germany.jpg" alt="Another Russian state-run media outlet, Ruptly, later reported that one of its editors had been detained after attempting to film the police action at the Sputnik office" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
           Another Russian state-run media outlet, Ruptly, later reported that one of its editors had been detained after attempting to film the police measures at the Sputnik office. Credits: RIA Novosti</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       In a rare escalation of judicial measures, Azerbaijan‚Äôs <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-authorities-have-sentenced" target="_blank">authorities have sentenced</a> the executive director and editor-in-chief of Russia's state-run news agency Sputnik to four months in prison. They were found guilty of fraud, illegal entrepreneurship, and legalization of property obtained by criminal measures. Azerbaijan‚Äôs Interior Ministry stated that Sputnik continued operating despite losing its accreditation in February 2025.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
    Russia called the arrests "unfriendly acts" and accused Azerbaijan of targeting journalists. The arrest follows the deaths of two ethnic Azerbaijanis in a Russian police raid in Yekaterinburg. Russian police have been profiling ethnic Azerbaijanis, including those with Russian citizenship, due to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-an-unresolved-murder-case" target="_blank">an unresolved murder case</a> from 2001.  </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      The recent arrest occurred just six months after the downing of an <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-azerbaijani-passenger-plane" target="_blank">Azerbaijani passenger plane</a> over Grozny in late 2024. President Vladimir Putin issued an apology for that event, but it was regarded as insincere by many. Recently, Azerbaijani President Aliyev did not attend Putin‚Äôs Victory Day parade in May, suggesting that the tensions are rising. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
