          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
    Germany‚Äôs immigrant integration issue
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
       Summary: 25% of the German immigrants want to exit Germany due to concerns about exclusion and high taxes. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Germany promises better job <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-opportunities-for-migrants" target="_blank">opportunities for migrants</a> and is one of the most sought-after countries for relocation. However, highly educated migrants are leaving Germany due to persistent discrimination and a lack of societal approval. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-25-people" target="_blank">25% people</a> are considering leaving, with reasons including exclusion, high taxes, bureaucracy, and political dissatisfaction. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Tax in Germany (14-45% on gains, 20% social contribution, 5.5% solidarity surcharge, and 8-9% church tax) is high due to the country‚Äôs commitment to funding its comprehensive <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-analysis-h1-10-social-welfare-system" target="_blank">social welfare system</a>. These taxes support universal healthcare, education, infrastructure, and social benefits, contributing to a better standard of living. However, many immigrants are taken aback by the extent of their tax obligations. They can also be confused by the bureaucratic system in accessing the services their taxes pay for. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          A 2024 study found that public concern about migration in Germany is on the rise. This trend was mirrored by the growing support for the far-right Alternative for Germany (AfD), which capitalized on migration anxieties in Germany's February 2025 election. While Germany needs more than <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-analysis-h1-11-40-000-immigrants" target="_blank">40,000 immigrants</a>, the states where the AfD party has a larger presence have reported difficulty in hiring foreign talent.  
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Economist Christian Dustmann emphasized that language remains crucial for integration. The immigrants also face <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-analysis-h1-12-housing-discrimination" target="_blank">housing discrimination</a>, underrepresentation in government, and an unequal gateway to high-paying jobs. Teachers and employers push migrant students into <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-analysis-h1-13-vocational-education-and-training" target="_blank">vocational education and training</a> early, reinforcing inequality. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Despite contributing to society, immigrants are met with mistrust, subtle bias, or outright xenophobia. Some of the fundamental challenges lie in changing cultural attitudes and promoting social inclusion.  
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
