          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-top:4px;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üáπüá≠ Thailand - PM suspended.</strong> 
           Thailand‚Äôs PM Paetongtarn Shinawatra was suspended after a leaked conversation with Cambodia‚Äôs Hun Sen sparked an ethics probe. Accused of undermining national interests, she faces mounting protests and coalition collapse. Although removed from her prime duties, she remains the Culture Minister (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-worldwide-14-thai-leaks" target="_blank">Thai leaks</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üáπüá∑ Turkey - Artists jailed.</strong> 
          Four people were detained in Turkey over a controversial LeMan magazine cartoon depicting Prophet Muhammad and Prophet Moses amid missile attacks. Authorities launched an investigation for ‚Äúinsulting religious values.‚Äù President Erdogan condemned the cartoon as a ‚Äúhate crime,‚Äù while <i>LeMan</i> apologized, claiming it highlighted Muslim suffering in Israeli attacks. (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-worldwide-15-trouble-with-cartoons" target="_blank">trouble with cartoons</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üáÆüá± Israel - Agrees to a ceasefire.</strong> 
           President Trump announced that Israel agreed to a US-backed 60-day Gaza ceasefire proposal, facilitated by Qatar and Egypt. The plan includes a hostage-prisoner exchange. Trump will meet Israeli PM Netanyahu next week, who is weighing whether to pursue a ceasefire or intensify attacks on Gaza (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-worldwide-16-road-to-peace" target="_blank">road to peace</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>üáµüá∞ Pakistan - Takes on presidency.</strong> 
          Pakistan has assumed the presidency of the UN Security Council for July, marking its first such term since 2013. Though largely symbolic, the role comes amid heightened India-Pakistan tensions following a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-worldwide-17-deadly-attack-in-kashmir" target="_blank">deadly attack in Kashmir</a>. Islamabad may spotlight Kashmir during its presidency, while New Delhi plans to counter with a focus on its economic strength and opposition to cross-border terrorism (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-worldwide-18-un-goals" target="_blank">UN goals</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>üá∫üá∏ USA - Foreign aid cuts.</strong> 
          A study warns that the Trump administration's cuts to USAID could result in 14Mn avoidable deaths by 2030, with a third being children under five. USAID had provided 40% of global humanitarian funding, preventing 91Mn deaths between 2001 and 2021. The funding reductions could reverse two decades of progress in health, particularly in low- and middle-income countries (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-worldwide-19-about-the-study" target="_blank">about the study</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>üáµüá± Poland - Border checks.</strong> 
          Poland will reintroduce temporary border controls with Germany and Lithuania on July 7 to curb illegal migration, following similar measures by Belgium, the Netherlands, and Germany. The move follows increased political pressure, with far-right opposition accusing the government of accepting illegal migrants (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-worldwide-20-interruptions-ahead" target="_blank">interruptions ahead</a>).
          </p>
        </mj-text>
