          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
   How is the next Dalai Lama going to be selected? 
 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/female-dalai-lama-reincarnation-the-tibet-museum.jpg" alt="The current Dalai Lama has said that there is no reason why a woman cannot be the next reincarnation" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i> The current Dalai Lama has said that there is no reason why a woman cannot be the next reincarnation. Credits: The Tibet Museum</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The selection of the next Dalai Lama is a complex process in <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-foundations-h1-21-tibetan-buddhism" target="_blank">Tibetan Buddhism</a>. After the death of the current Dalai Lama, it is believed that he will reincarnate as a young child. High lamas and officials from the Tibetan religious hierarchy then begin a years-long search. They look for spiritual visions, clues left by previous Dalai Lama, and signs like unusual births and behavior.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The current Dalai Lama is 90 years old. He believes that his successor will be born outside of China and has even suggested that he might train a successor during his existence, although this is uncertain. The Tibetan government-in-exile, based in India, plays a key role in this process. The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-foundations-h1-22-gaden-phodrang-foundation" target="_blank">Gaden Phodrang Foundation</a>, established by the Dalai Lama, will oversee the process of identifying his reincarnation.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       However, China disputes this and says that the Dalai Lama <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-jul-25-foundations-h1-23-must-be-chosen" target="_blank">must be chosen</a> in China. There is a decree from the 1793 Qing dynasty that details how to select a golden urn. The golden urn system involves writing the names of the three candidates on ivory slips, and a group of Tibetan elites would draw from it. However, this practice is outdated and hasn‚Äôt been consistently used by Tibetans for some time. Many feel that the Chinese government is using this old practice to yield control over choosing the next successor, preferably one that supports its government polices.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         In return, it would reduce Tibetan autonomy and influence. Tibet is strategically important for China. There have been several crackdowns on the province in the past. The Chinese communist party seeks to control its spiritual leadership. Tibetans, especially those in exile in India, fear that China might pick a "puppet" Dalai Lama. </p>

        </mj-text>
